1
00:01:38,817 --> 00:01:44,185
<b>GOD'S NOT DEAD 2</b>

2
00:01:45,815 --> 00:01:48,815
<b>Subrip: Pix</b>

3
00:03:44,205 --> 00:03:47,143
Brooke, we're all upset,
but we need to move on.

4
00:03:47,175 --> 00:03:49,411
Honey, you're a junior now.
It's your make-or-break year.

5
00:03:49,444 --> 00:03:51,680
So there's no room
for self pity.

6
00:03:53,314 --> 00:03:55,617
Can you give Marlene and I
a ride to school today?

7
00:03:55,651 --> 00:03:57,237
I'm sorry.
I don't have time.

8
00:03:57,238 --> 00:04:00,189
I have an 8:30 with Marc
Shelley at White & Wolfe.

9
00:04:00,222 --> 00:04:03,426
What? Richard, you didn't say anything!
How did you get the meeting?

10
00:04:03,459 --> 00:04:08,264
It's just a meeting, so don't get
too excited. But it could be huge.

11
00:04:08,296 --> 00:04:10,032
I know!

12
00:04:10,066 --> 00:04:11,601
Who's going to
the meeting with you?

13
00:04:11,602 --> 00:04:13,135
Hey, I got the meeting.

14
00:04:13,169 --> 00:04:15,638
I just think maybe you should
take Melinda or Janice.

15
00:04:15,670 --> 00:04:17,639
Janice? You want
me to take Janice?

16
00:04:17,673 --> 00:04:19,274
-Yeah. Why not?
-I'm not taking Janice.

17
00:04:19,307 --> 00:04:22,110
-Rough morning?
-You know my parents.

18
00:04:22,144 --> 00:04:25,180
Maybe they just
need a little more time.

19
00:04:25,213 --> 00:04:28,050
I don't know
about that.

20
00:04:28,084 --> 00:04:30,218
I'd say they're
pretty over it.

21
00:04:30,252 --> 00:04:35,223
My mom's making tacos tonight.
I'll let her know you're coming.

22
00:04:35,257 --> 00:04:37,126
It's not like
they'll miss me.

23
00:04:37,158 --> 00:04:40,730
Brooke, I'm serious, honey.
You need to get focused.

24
00:04:40,762 --> 00:04:44,199
Or you can say, "Good-bye,
Stanford, hello, Somewhere State."

25
00:04:44,233 --> 00:04:45,769
Got it.

26
00:04:49,572 --> 00:04:51,774
Yikes.

27
00:04:51,807 --> 00:04:53,158
Good morning!

28
00:04:53,159 --> 00:04:54,509
Morning, Grace.

29
00:04:54,543 --> 00:04:57,312
You don't have to
keep doing this.

30
00:04:57,346 --> 00:04:59,615
Are you kidding? This is the
best part of my day, Gramps.

31
00:04:59,648 --> 00:05:02,218
Well, pills first.

32
00:05:02,250 --> 00:05:04,286
You're a good girl.

33
00:05:06,488 --> 00:05:09,625
Honey, you know I'm not
gonna be around here forever,

34
00:05:09,658 --> 00:05:13,830
and you might wanna start
thinking about some other guy

35
00:05:13,862 --> 00:05:16,065
you wanna have breakfast with.

36
00:05:16,899 --> 00:05:18,434
I'll work on that.

37
00:05:18,466 --> 00:05:21,437
Okay.

38
00:05:21,470 --> 00:05:23,739
You know, I love the way
you do the oatmeal,

39
00:05:23,771 --> 00:05:28,110
but what do you say I take you out
for bacon and eggs this morning.

40
00:05:28,144 --> 00:05:29,579
My treat.

41
00:05:29,612 --> 00:05:32,215
Not after your
last cholesterol test.

42
00:05:32,247 --> 00:05:35,117
Besides, I have some papers I have
to grade before the staff meeting.

43
00:05:35,151 --> 00:05:39,355
I'm 81 years old, and bacon is
not gonna be what kills me.

44
00:05:39,387 --> 00:05:42,558
Nice try. You're 82.

45
00:05:47,896 --> 00:05:49,598
Yeah.

46
00:05:49,632 --> 00:05:52,668
-Good morning.
-Have a nice day.

47
00:05:52,701 --> 00:05:54,370
Morning, ladies.
Morning.

48
00:05:55,637 --> 00:05:58,207
Good morning.

49
00:06:01,776 --> 00:06:05,281
Hey, what do you call
a teacher with no students?

50
00:06:05,314 --> 00:06:06,682
Unemployed.

51
00:06:06,714 --> 00:06:08,450
I got it.
How about ecstatic?

52
00:06:08,483 --> 00:06:10,685
You're both right.
Retired.

53
00:06:10,718 --> 00:06:13,656
Only 36 days to go.

54
00:06:13,689 --> 00:06:16,492
You're gonna miss the kids
when you're gone, Rizzo.

55
00:06:16,524 --> 00:06:19,495
No, Grace, that's sweet,
but no, I won't.

56
00:06:19,528 --> 00:06:22,564
The older I get, the more difficult
these kids are to deal with.

57
00:06:22,598 --> 00:06:25,168
I totally agree. Yesterday, I just
about snapped at Tim Webster.

58
00:06:25,201 --> 00:06:27,170
That boy had me
on my last nerve.

59
00:06:27,202 --> 00:06:30,205
Well, I happen to think that difficult
students can be a blessing.

60
00:06:30,238 --> 00:06:32,774
Grace, honey, when is this
optimism ever gonna wear off?

61
00:06:37,779 --> 00:06:39,347
Bill.

62
00:06:39,380 --> 00:06:40,882
Bill.

63
00:06:40,915 --> 00:06:42,618
Bill.

64
00:06:44,620 --> 00:06:46,288
Junk mail.

65
00:06:48,223 --> 00:06:49,791
Man!

66
00:06:49,824 --> 00:06:53,795
David, why are
you always so sad?

67
00:06:53,829 --> 00:06:57,833
Hey! You're back.
Why are you back?

68
00:06:57,865 --> 00:07:01,570
My pastor gave me permission to
finish my doctorate at Hadleigh,

69
00:07:01,603 --> 00:07:04,973
so if that's okay with you,
I'm gonna be here for a while.

70
00:07:06,975 --> 00:07:09,845
David, you are a mess.
What happened to you?

71
00:07:09,877 --> 00:07:11,514
I woke up.

72
00:07:14,283 --> 00:07:18,687
Okay, for 500 points, for all
the cheese, for the game.

73
00:07:18,721 --> 00:07:21,723
This quote
is from what document?

74
00:07:21,757 --> 00:07:23,959
"We hold these truths
to be self-evident,

75
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:25,427
that all men are created equal,

76
00:07:25,461 --> 00:07:27,797
that they are endowed by their creator
with certain unalienable rights..."

77
00:07:27,829 --> 00:07:30,665
Boom, baby!

78
00:07:30,699 --> 00:07:32,401
Team 1,
what's your answer?

79
00:07:32,434 --> 00:07:34,470
Our answer is the Declaration
of Independence.

80
00:07:35,571 --> 00:07:37,506
That's...

81
00:07:37,538 --> 00:07:39,541
correct!
Team 1 wins!

82
00:07:42,877 --> 00:07:45,909
Okay, monday we will
examine the assertion

83
00:07:45,910 --> 00:07:49,685
of individual rights through the
last century. Have a good weekend.

84
00:07:53,855 --> 00:07:56,725
Brooke, are you okay?

85
00:07:56,759 --> 00:07:58,694
I'm fine.

86
00:07:59,495 --> 00:08:00,896
Are you sure?

87
00:08:00,928 --> 00:08:03,265
Yeah, thanks.

88
00:08:18,514 --> 00:08:19,848
Ms. Ryan?

89
00:08:42,538 --> 00:08:44,573
I lied.

90
00:08:47,676 --> 00:08:49,745
Are you sure
you're being fair?

91
00:08:49,778 --> 00:08:54,082
Trust me. They're over it. And
they expect me to be over it too.

92
00:08:54,115 --> 00:08:57,819
It's like to them
never even existed.

93
00:08:57,852 --> 00:08:59,688
The only thing
that I know for sure

94
00:08:59,721 --> 00:09:03,425
is that I'm never going
to see my brother again.

95
00:09:03,458 --> 00:09:05,527
Everybody's asked if there's
anything that they can do.

96
00:09:05,561 --> 00:09:07,797
The truth is,
no one can do anything

97
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:10,432
because the only thing I really
want is five more minutes

98
00:09:10,466 --> 00:09:13,668
to tell my brother
how I really felt about him.

99
00:09:13,701 --> 00:09:16,773
Did you brother believe
there was something more?

100
00:09:17,706 --> 00:09:19,608
I don't know.

101
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:21,043
Do you?

102
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:26,251
Brooke, every person
reaches a point in their

103
00:09:26,252 --> 00:09:27,983
life when they ask
themselves this question.

104
00:09:28,015 --> 00:09:31,553
There's nothing wrong
with you asking it too.

105
00:09:33,889 --> 00:09:36,558
You never let anything
get to you.

106
00:09:36,591 --> 00:09:38,694
How do you do that?

107
00:09:40,995 --> 00:09:42,597
Jesus.

108
00:10:03,951 --> 00:10:05,153
Hello?

109
00:10:05,187 --> 00:10:07,389
How'd it go, Amy?

110
00:10:07,423 --> 00:10:08,658
<i>Michael.</i>

111
00:10:09,991 --> 00:10:11,927
It's gone.

112
00:10:13,461 --> 00:10:16,631
My cancer's... It's gone.

113
00:10:16,664 --> 00:10:18,800
My goodness!

114
00:10:18,833 --> 00:10:20,836
That's incredible!

115
00:10:20,837 --> 00:10:22,838
<i>I know. I just...</i>

116
00:10:23,938 --> 00:10:25,140
I can't believe it.

117
00:10:26,808 --> 00:10:28,810
Isn't that
what you prayed for?

118
00:10:28,844 --> 00:10:30,413
Yes, of course.
I just...

119
00:10:32,748 --> 00:10:35,551
Prayer
is a powerful thing,

120
00:10:35,583 --> 00:10:39,554
and it turns out God has
much bigger plans for you.

121
00:10:50,065 --> 00:10:52,435
You okay, Grace?

122
00:10:52,467 --> 00:10:54,937
Yeah, I just can't stop
thinking about Brooke.

123
00:10:54,970 --> 00:10:58,106
You know, she's searching.
She's hurting.

124
00:10:58,139 --> 00:11:02,144
Yeah, that's the thing
about atheism.

125
00:11:02,177 --> 00:11:05,915
It doesn't take away the pain.
It just takes away the hope.

126
00:11:07,048 --> 00:11:08,500
What'd you tell her?

127
00:11:08,501 --> 00:11:09,951
The truth.

128
00:11:09,985 --> 00:11:12,988
Now she's free to
make her own choice.

129
00:11:13,020 --> 00:11:15,591
Unfortunately,
in this day and age,

130
00:11:15,624 --> 00:11:19,628
people seem to forget that the
most basic human right of all

131
00:11:19,660 --> 00:11:21,763
is the right
to know Jesus.

132
00:11:21,797 --> 00:11:23,865
Let's put her
on the prayer list.

133
00:11:23,899 --> 00:11:27,068
Prayer always seems to be
the last thing we do,

134
00:11:27,101 --> 00:11:29,538
when it should be the first.

135
00:11:31,038 --> 00:11:33,107
Now, how 'bout
some more popcorn?

136
00:11:33,140 --> 00:11:36,945
With a glycemic index
of 100, not a chance.

137
00:11:36,979 --> 00:11:39,148
I swear, Grace, if you
don't start feeding me better,

138
00:11:39,181 --> 00:11:41,684
I'm gonna leave you
for a nursing home.

139
00:11:42,817 --> 00:11:45,086
Well, that's it for me.

140
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:46,956
I'm going to bed.

141
00:11:46,989 --> 00:11:48,157
Love ya.

142
00:11:48,190 --> 00:11:50,192
I love you better.

143
00:11:50,225 --> 00:11:52,094
Love you first.

144
00:11:52,126 --> 00:11:53,862
That's unfair.

145
00:11:55,730 --> 00:11:57,667
Gotcha!

146
00:12:02,604 --> 00:12:04,298
Brooke,

147
00:12:04,299 --> 00:12:06,642
the people from that charity place are
here to pick up your brother's things.

148
00:12:06,674 --> 00:12:09,144
Can you make sure
they get everything?

149
00:12:10,312 --> 00:12:12,882
And don't forget to
put the milk away!

150
00:13:37,899 --> 00:13:40,369
Well,
that's the last of it.

151
00:13:40,402 --> 00:13:42,271
Thank you.

152
00:13:42,303 --> 00:13:45,374
And while I was loading one
of the boxes onto the truck,

153
00:13:45,407 --> 00:13:49,812
I noticed this and I thought
you might want to keep it.

154
00:13:49,845 --> 00:13:51,614
So sorry for your loss.

155
00:14:35,356 --> 00:14:39,995
So peaceful nonviolence comes
first in India under Gandhi,

156
00:14:40,028 --> 00:14:43,298
and then later, here in the United
States under Dr. King and others

157
00:14:43,331 --> 00:14:45,734
as a means of
achieving civil rights.

158
00:14:45,767 --> 00:14:48,903
But what makes
nonviolence so radical

159
00:14:48,937 --> 00:14:51,940
is its unwavering commitment
to a nonviolent approach,

160
00:14:51,972 --> 00:14:55,144
not just initially, but in the
face of escalating persecution

161
00:14:55,177 --> 00:14:57,745
by the opposing force.

162
00:14:57,778 --> 00:14:59,313
Yes?

163
00:14:59,346 --> 00:15:02,016
Isn't that sort of
like what Jesus meant

164
00:15:02,049 --> 00:15:04,853
when said that we
should love our enemies?

165
00:15:07,121 --> 00:15:09,190
Yes.

166
00:15:09,224 --> 00:15:12,094
The writer
of the gospel of Matthew

167
00:15:12,126 --> 00:15:14,929
records Jesus as saying,
"You have heard it said,

168
00:15:14,962 --> 00:15:17,298
love your neighbor
and hate your enemy,

169
00:15:17,331 --> 00:15:20,302
but I tell you,
love your enemies

170
00:15:20,335 --> 00:15:23,172
and pray for those
who persecute you,

171
00:15:23,205 --> 00:15:26,075
that you will be children
of your father in heaven,"

172
00:15:26,107 --> 00:15:29,277
which indicates
a commitment to nonviolence.

173
00:15:29,311 --> 00:15:33,215
Dr. King confirmed the link, describing
his inspiration from Scripture,

174
00:15:33,248 --> 00:15:36,884
saying Christ furnished
the spirit and motivation,

175
00:15:36,918 --> 00:15:38,419
while Gandhi
furnished the method.

176
00:15:38,452 --> 00:15:43,858
Except that that didn't work. Jesus got
himself killed. Everybody knows that.

177
00:15:43,892 --> 00:15:46,361
Well, so did Dr. King.

178
00:15:46,394 --> 00:15:50,932
So I guess it just depends
on how you measure success.

179
00:15:50,966 --> 00:15:53,435
Both men created movements
that survive to this day,

180
00:15:53,467 --> 00:15:56,270
even though both
paid the ultimate price

181
00:15:56,303 --> 00:15:58,139
for their commitment
to their ideals.

182
00:15:58,173 --> 00:16:00,109
I still wouldn't do it.

183
00:16:00,142 --> 00:16:02,945
Well, not very many people
have that kind of courage.

184
00:16:02,977 --> 00:16:06,013
But I, for one, am grateful
for those that do,

185
00:16:06,047 --> 00:16:10,018
you know, those who stand up
for what they believe.

186
00:16:15,490 --> 00:16:17,158
Have a good day.

187
00:16:31,807 --> 00:16:33,274
Are you Pastor Dave?

188
00:16:33,307 --> 00:16:34,809
I am.

189
00:16:34,842 --> 00:16:35,910
I'm Martin Yip.

190
00:16:35,911 --> 00:16:36,978
Nice to meet you.

191
00:16:37,011 --> 00:16:39,947
My friend Josh Wheaton
said you might be able

192
00:16:39,980 --> 00:16:42,451
to answer my questions
about God.

193
00:16:42,484 --> 00:16:45,321
Well, that definitely falls
within my job description.

194
00:16:47,822 --> 00:16:49,357
How many questions
have you got?

195
00:16:49,390 --> 00:16:52,060
So far, 147.

196
00:16:54,328 --> 00:16:55,813
Is something wrong?

197
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:57,298
No.

198
00:16:57,331 --> 00:17:00,903
Josh encouraged me to write them down
and be as comprehensive as possible.

199
00:17:00,936 --> 00:17:03,872
Of course did. I'll have to
thank him next time I see him.

200
00:17:03,904 --> 00:17:05,106
Come on.

201
00:17:05,140 --> 00:17:06,909
So, what's
your first question?

202
00:17:08,542 --> 00:17:12,548
Grace, I just have
to hear it from you.

203
00:17:12,580 --> 00:17:14,549
Did this happen?

204
00:17:14,583 --> 00:17:18,954
If you're asking whether I responded
to a student's question, yes.

205
00:17:18,987 --> 00:17:22,356
If you're asking whether
her question and my answer

206
00:17:22,390 --> 00:17:23,923
both referenced Jesus
as it was relevant

207
00:17:23,924 --> 00:17:28,090
to the history lesson we were
discussing, again, I'd have to say...

208
00:17:28,091 --> 00:17:29,244
yes.

209
00:17:32,500 --> 00:17:34,804
Good afternoon,
Ms. Wesley.

210
00:17:39,340 --> 00:17:43,846
I've asked Bob Fessler to sit
in... he's the school's attorney...

211
00:17:43,878 --> 00:17:47,548
To advise us on any legal issues
we might be brushing up against.

212
00:17:47,582 --> 00:17:50,052
Should I have
a lawyer too?

213
00:17:50,085 --> 00:17:52,520
I don't see
the need for that.

214
00:17:52,554 --> 00:17:55,423
Ms. Rizzo is present
as your union representation.

215
00:17:57,325 --> 00:17:59,061
Okay.

216
00:17:59,094 --> 00:18:01,897
We are here to hear
your side of the story.

217
00:18:01,930 --> 00:18:06,468
Now, I understand a student in
your second-period history class

218
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:08,936
asked a question
about the parallels

219
00:18:08,970 --> 00:18:11,440
between
the teachings of Gandhi

220
00:18:11,472 --> 00:18:13,509
and remarks
allegedly made by Jesus.

221
00:18:15,042 --> 00:18:17,111
Yes, that's correct.

222
00:18:17,144 --> 00:18:22,617
And your answer incorporated specific
detailed reference to those teachings

223
00:18:22,651 --> 00:18:24,486
that included
Scripture itself,

224
00:18:25,619 --> 00:18:27,255
the words of Jesus.

225
00:18:28,690 --> 00:18:30,292
Yes.

226
00:18:30,325 --> 00:18:33,061
What were you thinking,
Grace?

227
00:18:33,094 --> 00:18:37,499
Do you believe your response was
in line with district policy?

228
00:18:37,531 --> 00:18:39,667
Yes.

229
00:18:39,701 --> 00:18:44,405
As well as in compliance with
state and federal guidelines?

230
00:18:45,440 --> 00:18:47,276
Yes, sir.

231
00:18:47,308 --> 00:18:49,110
Well, Ms. Wesley,

232
00:18:51,112 --> 00:18:53,115
unfortunately for you,

233
00:18:53,147 --> 00:18:56,951
I'm fairly certain the
school board will disagree.

234
00:19:00,587 --> 00:19:03,057
No, Coach,
you're not hearing me.

235
00:19:03,090 --> 00:19:04,926
No prayers.

236
00:19:04,960 --> 00:19:08,196
No moments of silence.
Nothing.

237
00:19:08,229 --> 00:19:09,932
<i>It's tradition
on the field.</i>

238
00:19:09,964 --> 00:19:12,067
Not on the field,
not in the locker room,

239
00:19:12,099 --> 00:19:14,302
not in the parking lot
for that matter, okay?

240
00:19:14,336 --> 00:19:16,171
<i>-Whatever you say.
-Okay, thanks, Coach.</i>

241
00:19:16,203 --> 00:19:18,139
Come on in.

242
00:19:18,173 --> 00:19:21,375
-Hi, Brooke.
-You wanted to see me?

243
00:19:21,409 --> 00:19:25,047
Ms. Wesley is currently
under disciplinary review.

244
00:19:25,079 --> 00:19:28,250
All of her classes have been
reassigned until things are settled.

245
00:19:28,282 --> 00:19:30,351
I don't want you to have
any contact with her.

246
00:19:30,384 --> 00:19:33,454
None whatsoever, either
on or off school property.

247
00:19:33,488 --> 00:19:35,390
Do I have any say in this?

248
00:19:35,423 --> 00:19:39,728
No, I've already discussed things
with your father and agrees.

249
00:19:39,760 --> 00:19:41,963
Since when
does my dad care?

250
00:19:41,997 --> 00:19:46,201
Brooke, the important thing for you to
remember is you've done nothing wrong.

251
00:19:46,233 --> 00:19:48,669
Neither did Ms. Wesley. All she
did was answer a question.

252
00:19:48,702 --> 00:19:52,307
Ms. Wesley's answer was not in
line with school policy. -Really?

